When someone write deviation like this, 

```
  deviation /rm:resetVpnv6statistics {
    deviate not-supported;
  }
  deviation /rm:resetVpnv6statistics {
    deviate not-supported;
  }
```

pyang will throw an exception and terminate the process.
`idx = t.parent.i_children.index(t)` at <statements.py>

Is there a better way to deal with "duplicate define" of "deviate not-support"?
I suggest let the program continue to run, but record the error log.

I analyzed loss_mmod_::compute_loss_value_and_gradient() and compared it with the original document https://arxiv.org/pdf/1502.00046.pdf. I found several potential bugs I would like to discuss.
**---- #1 ----**
In the document describing the algorithm to perform MMOD object detection on page 5, in the pseudo code of the algorithm on line 5 there is: 
_if D i does not overlap {D i−1 ,D i−2 ,...} then_
In c++ implementation there is:
               _for (unsigned long i = 0; i < dets.size() && final_dets.size() < max_num_dets; ++i)
                {
                    if (overlaps_any_box_nms(final_dets, dets[i].rect))
                        continue;
                    const std::pair<double,unsigned int> hittruth = find_best_match(*truth, dets[i].rect);
                    final_dets.push_back(dets[i].rect);_

Let's consider this case: set of detections contains 3 detections in following configuration: D1 overlaps D2, D2 overlaps D3 but D3 does not overlap D1.
Difference: **pseudocode algorithm would process only D1, C++ implementation would process D1 and D3.**

**---- #2 ----**
In c++ code there is a loop over all input samples (images): 
            _const float* out_data = output_tensor.host();
            for (long i = 0; i < output_tensor.num_samples(); ++i)
            {
                tensor_to_dets(input_tensor, output_tensor, i, dets, -options.loss_per_false_alarm, sub);
                .....
                for (auto&& x : *truth)
                {
                    if (!x.ignore)
                    {
                        point p = image_rect_to_feat_coord(input_tensor, x, sub);
                        loss -= out_data[p.y()*output_tensor.nc() + p.x()];_
  
While method **tensor_to_dets** takes into account index i of the processed image and adjusts pointer to raw data like this: _const float* out_data = output_tensor.host() + output_tensor.nr()*output_tensor.nc()*i;_
it is forgotten in the loss calculation here:  _loss -= out_data[p.y()*output_tensor.nc() + p.x()];_
The same problem occurs at the end of the cycle:
               _for (auto&& x : final_dets)
                {
                    loss += out_data[x.tensor_offset];_
Here _tensor_offset_ again does not contain the image index adjustment. 
**In both cases output data of the 1st image is used in the particular calculation for all of the images.

	@asyncio.coroutine
	def send(self, conversation, message, image=None):
		yield from conversation.send_message(hangups.ChatMessageSegment.from_str(message), image_file=image)

Currently, the filepath of the image is being passed to send(), but neither the message nor the image is sending. However, if no image is passed, the message can be sent. Does send_message support image sending or is there another way to implement this? Sorry if this is a duplicate.

I'm using [locals](https://www.terraform.io/docs/configuration/locals.html) in my main.tf file for tagging values and then using them to simplify tagging of other resources like so:
````
$ cat main.tf
...
locals {
  tagging_standard = {
    "Environment" = "Development"
    "Description" = "<some description>"
    "Application" = "app1"
    "Creator"     = "joebob"
...
  }
}

$ cat vpc.tf
...
resource "aws_default_route_table" "r" {
  default_route_table_id = "${aws_vpc.vpc.default_route_table_id}"

  route {
    cidr_block = "0.0.0.0/0"
    gateway_id = "${aws_internet_gateway.gw.id}"
  }

  tags = "${local.tagging_standard}"
}
````

When I try to use pyhcl to parse the hcl/tf files, it doesn't resolve them, and instead includes them as strings:
````
$ hcltool /path/to/terraform/vpc.tf
{
    "resource": {
        "aws_default_route_table": {
            "r": {
                "default_route_table_id": "${aws_vpc.vpc.default_route_table_id}",
                "route": {
                    "cidr_block": "0.0.0.0/0",
                    "gateway_id": "${aws_internet_gateway.gw.id}"
                },
                "tags": "${local.tagging_standard}"
            }
        },
...
````
Expected behavior:
````
$ hcltool /path/to/terraform/vpc.tf
{
    "resource": {
        "aws_default_route_table": {
            "r": {
                "default_route_table_id": "${aws_vpc.vpc.default_route_table_id}",
                "route": {
                    "cidr_block": "0.0.0.0/0",
                    "gateway_id": "${aws_internet_gateway.gw.id}"
                },
                "tags": {
                    "Environment" = "Development",
                    "Description" = "<some description>",
                    "Application" = "app1",
                    "Creator"     = "joebob"
                }
            }
        },
...
````

Is there another way to get pyhcl to traverse a whole project and do this translation like the terraform cli does? Thanks!

I'm working on a small Flask application using uwsgi threading to pull at regular intervals from a database connected to through an ssh tunnel. 

When I launch the application with a ssh tunnel outside of the thread it starts up perfectly fine, yet when I move the tunnel into the thread none of my routes load and I end up getting timeout errors.

This is launched using the tiangolo/uwsgi-nginx-flask:python3.6 docker container. I have multi-threading enabled within my uwsgi.ini file as well. 

I'm not sure if it's a uwsgi error, sshtunnel error, or if I'm just missing something else entirely, but any help/guidance would be greatly appreciated.

**Working Flask Startup:**
`
